  "prompt": "How do physicians decide whether to subscribe a new drug/therapy when the expected benefit is unclear and still no HTA-assessment available?",
  "response": "Physicians consider several factors when deciding whether to prescribe a new drug or therapy without a completed Health Technology Assessment (HTA):\n\n1. Scientific Evidence\n- Published clinical trials\n- Preliminary research data\n- Peer-reviewed journal publications\n- Expert consensus statements\n- Preliminary meta-analyses\n\n2. Risk-Benefit Assessment\n- Potential therapeutic benefits\n- Known side effects\n- Comparison with existing treatments\n- Patient-specific risk factors\n- Potential for improved outcomes\n\n3. Professional Guidelines\n- Recommendations from specialty medical societies\n- Interim clinical practice guidelines\n- Expert panel recommendations\n- Consensus statements from professional organizations\n\n4. Patient-Specific Considerations\n- Individual patient's medical history\n- Existing comorbidities\n- Previous treatment responses\n- Patient's risk tolerance\n- Potential quality of life improvements\n\n5. Regulatory Information\n- Preliminary FDA/EMA approvals\n- Ongoing clinical trials\n- Compassionate use protocols\n- Emergency use authorizations\n\n6. Consultation and Collaboration\n- Discussions with colleagues\n- Multidisciplinary team consultations\n- Input from specialist experts\n- Peer review and discussion\n\n7. Precautionary Principles\n- Careful patient monitoring\n- Informed consent\n- Transparent communication about uncertainties\n- Willingness to discontinue if adverse effects emerge\n\nThese factors help physicians make informed, responsible decisions in the absence of comprehensive HTA assessments.",
